The mistake has been honest, but it has certainly been caused by the lack of fellowship and of that charity which St. Paul says is credulous and hopeful of all endeavour. At its root, near or far, probably lies the desire to attain heaven rather than to give lavishly to God and man. But whatever its cause, its results are obvious. Let us lay them before its advocates. Granted that the greater part of all works of artistic worth are ungodly‚ whose the fault? Art cannot be did- actic; it can be wholesome and recrea- tive; it can be true, holy, glorious. If it is not this, the irreligious, whom you consider its sole authors and patrons, are not to blame. What could sinners bring forth but sin? The power was there for your using3 if you, the good, have not used it, how can you expect the product to be good?
